The six odes which follow are, more or less, on the same theme. As Mr. Wickham puts it in his introduction to the Third Book of the Odes—“ The unity of purpose is obvious. The ends social‚ moral, religious, political‚ which a good government should set before itself in Rome are reviewed‚ and it is more than once promised that Caesar’s reggime is to compass thern.'' XVIII. is conceived in the same spirit, and may be added to the list.

XIX. belongs to the year 27, when Augustus left Rome with the intention of invading Britain.
